* * * The freedom of arrangement possible in an in- flected language and required by the exigencies of the metre yields effects of symmetry, parallelism, antithesis, and inter- locked order which will be felt by any one who reads the odes familiarly, but cannot be reproduced in English. As many as five words may intervene between a noun and its modifier, and the order within such a group may reproduce or reverse that of the extremes. In this way a thought is suspended, a picture is gradually unfolded, a name is reserved for a climax, etc.'' -Snonnn
